predict.capital_turnover_ratio_formula_d.defaultMessage: It measures how effectively you are utilising working capital to generate sales. Average working capital is your current assets less current liabilities averaged over 12 months. A lower score would suggest poor sales generation but could indicate bad debts or obsolete inventory. A higher score is generally better however a very high figure could indicaste additional assets should be acquired to fund growth. A high level of unpaid bills can artificially inflate this figure. predict.cash_ratio_formula_description.defaultMessage: This liquidity metric measures business risk by looking at how your cash could be used to meet short term obligations. A ratio of 2 would mean that current liabilities could be paid off twice with your current cash balance. A score of 1 is typically considered good for a relevant liquidity measure but there are other factors. If you have unpaid invoices or stock that can readily be turned into cash, the quick or current ratio may be a better measure of your liquidity. Long term debt repayments, risk of customers defaulting and highly variable cashflows may mean a score of 1 is not enough.
